The '''red-headed myzomela''' or '''red-headed honeyeater''' ('''''Myzomela erythrocephala''''') is a [[passerine]] bird of the [[honeyeater]] family Meliphagidae found in [[Australia]], [[Indonesia]], and [[Papua New Guinea]]. It was [[Species description|describe]]d by [[John Gould]] in 1840. Two [[subspecies]] are recognised, with the [[Subspecies#Nominotypical subspecies and subspecies autonyms|nominate race]] ''M.&nbsp;e. erythrocephala'' distributed around the tropical coastline of Australia, and ''M.&nbsp;e. infuscata'' in New Guinea. Though widely distributed, the species is not abundant within this range. While the [[IUCN]] lists the Australian population of ''M.&nbsp;e. infuscata'' as being [[near threatened]], as a whole the widespread range means that its conservation is of [[least concern]].

At {{cvt|12|cm|in|abbr=on}}, it is a small honeyeater with a short tail and relatively long down-curved bill. It is [[Sexual dimorphism|sexually dimorphic]]; the male has a glossy red head and brown upperparts and paler grey-brown underparts while the female has predominantly grey-brown plumage. Its natural [[habitat]] is subtropical or tropical [[mangrove]] forests. It is very active when feeding in the [[Canopy (biology)|tree canopy]], darting from flower to flower and [[Gleaning (birds)|glean]]ing insects off foliage. It calls constantly as it feeds. While little has been documented on the red-headed myzomela's breeding behaviour, it is recorded as building a small cup-shaped nest in the mangroves and laying two or three oval, white eggs with small red blotches.

== Taxonomy ==
The red-headed myzomela was described and named as ''Myzomela erythrocephala'' by [[John Gould]] in 1840,<ref name="gould1840">{{cite journal|last=Gould|first=John|date=1840|title=Letter to Chairman of the Scientific Committee, Zoological Society of London, read before meeting of the Society of Oct. 8, 1839|journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London|volume=7|pages=139–145 [144]|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/30571387}}</ref> from specimens collected in [[King Sound]] in northern [[Western Australia]].<ref name="AFD">{{cite web|url=https://biodiversity.org.au/afd/taxa/Myzomela_%28Myzomela%29_erythrocephala_erythrocephala|title=Subspecies ''Myzomela (Myzomela) erythrocephala erythrocephala'' Gould, 1840|author=Australian Biological Resources Study|date=30 August 2011|work=Australian Faunal Directory|publisher=Department of the Environment, Water, Heritage and the Arts, Australian Government|access-date=23 January 2017|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory}}</ref> The [[genus]] name is derived from the [[Ancient Greek]] words {{Lang|grc-Latn|myzo}} (to suckle) and {{Lang|grc-Latn|meli}} (honey), and refers to the bird's [[Nectarivore|nectarivorous]] habits, while ''erythrocephala'' is from the Greek ''erythros'' (red) and ''-kephale'' (head).<ref name="Liddell 1980">{{cite book|first1=Henry George|last1=Liddell|author-link=Henry George Liddell|first2=Robert|last2=Scott|author-link2=Robert Scott (philologist)|year=1980|orig-date=1871|title=A Greek-English Lexicon|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|location=Oxford, United Kingdom|isbn=0-19-910207-4|pages=[https://archive.org/details/lexicon00lidd/page/272 272, 374]|url=https://archive.org/details/lexicon00lidd/page/272|edition=Abridged }}</ref> This species was known as the red-headed honeyeater in Australia, and red-headed myzomela elsewhere,<ref name=fraser13>{{cite book|last1=Gray|first1=Jeannie|last2=Fraser|first2=Ian|title=Australian Bird Names: A Complete Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W1TCqHVWQp0C&pg=PT209|year=2013|publisher=Csiro Publishing|location=Collingwood, Victoria|isbn=978-0-643-10471-6|page=209}}</ref> the latter name being adopted as the official name by the [[International Ornithological Committee]] (IOC).<ref name="ioclist">{{cite web|editor1-last=Gill|editor1-first=Frank|editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist)|editor2-last=Donsker|editor2-first=David|year=2017|title=Honeyeaters|work=World Bird List Version 7.1|url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/honeyeaters/|publisher=International Ornithologists' Union|access-date=25 February 2017 }}</ref> Other common names are mangrove red-headed honeyeater, mangrove redhead, and blood-bird.<ref name=fraser13/>

Two subspecies are recognised:<ref name="ioclist"/> the nominate [[Race (taxonomy)|race]] ''M.&nbsp;e. erythrocephala'', and ''M.&nbsp;e. infuscata'', which was described by [[William Alexander Forbes]] in 1879 from a specimen collected from Hall Bay in southern New Guinea. Forbes noted there was more red on the back, and the upperparts are a lighter brown.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Forbes, William Alexander|year=1879|title=A synopsis of the Meliphaginae, genus ''Myzomela'', with descriptions of two new species|journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London|volume=1879:Jan.-Mar. |pages=256–278 [263]|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/28520749}}</ref> The [[Sumba myzomela]] (''Myzomela dammermani''{{--)}} was until 2008 regarded as a subspecies of the red-headed myzomela,<ref name="ioclist"/> as was the [[Wetar myzomela]] (''M.&nbsp;kuehni''{{--)}}, which is [[Endemism|endemic]] to the Indonesian island of [[Wetar]].{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1164}}

The red-headed myzomela is a member of the genus ''[[Myzomela]]'' which includes two other Australian species, the [[scarlet myzomela]] of eastern Australia, and the [[dusky myzomela]] of northern Australia. It belongs to the [[honeyeater]] family Meliphagidae.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Systematics and Taxonomy of Australian Birds|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=klm159tsD-oC&pg=PA187|page=187|publisher=Csiro Publishing|location=Collingwood, Victoria|date=2008|isbn=978-0-643-06511-6|first1=Les|last1=Christidis|first2=Walter|last2=Boles}}</ref> A 2004 [[Genetics|genetic]] study of [[Nuclear DNA|nuclear]] and [[Mitochondrial DNA|mitochondrial]] [[DNA]] of honeyeaters found it to be the next closest relative to a smaller group consisting of the scarlet and [[cardinal myzomela]]s, although only five of the thirty members of the genus ''Myzomela'' were analysed.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Driskell|first1=Amy C.|last2=Christidis|first2=Les|year=2004|title=Phylogeny and evolution of the Australo–Papuan honeyeaters (Passeriformes, Meliphagidae)|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|pmid=15120392|volume=31|issue=3|pages=943–960|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2003.10.017|bibcode=2004MolPE..31..943D }}</ref> A 2017 genetic study using both mitochondrial and nuclear DNA suggests that the ancestor of the red-headed myzomela diverged from that of the [[black-breasted myzomela]] around four million years ago; however, the relationships of many species within the genus are uncertain.<ref name="Marki 2017">{{cite journal|author=Marki, Petter Z.|author2=Jønsson, Knud A.|author3=Irestedt, Martin|author4=Nguyen, Jacqueline M.T.|author5=Rahbek, Carsten|author6=Fjeldså, Jon|date=2017|title=Supermatrix phylogeny and biogeography of the Australasian Meliphagides radiation (Aves: Passeriformes)|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=107|pages=516–529|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2016.12.021|pmid=28017855|bibcode=2017MolPE.107..516M |hdl=10852/65203|hdl-access=free}}</ref> [[Molecule|Molecular]] analysis has shown that honeyeaters are related to the [[Pardalotidae]] (pardalotes), [[Acanthizidae]] (Australian warblers, scrubwrens, thornbills, etc.), and the [[Maluridae]] (Australian fairy-wrens) in the large superfamily [[Meliphagoidea]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Barker|first1=F. Keith|last2=Cibois|first2=Alice|last3=Schikler|first3=Peter|last4=Feinstein|first4=Julie|last5=Cracraft|first5=Joel|year=2004|title=Phylogeny and diversification of the largest avian radiation|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA|volume=101|issue=30|pages=11040–45|doi=10.1073/pnas.0401892101|pmc=503738|pmid=15263073|bibcode=2004PNAS..10111040B|doi-access=free}}</ref> Because the red-headed myzomela occurs on many offshore islands and appears to be an effective water-crosser, it has been [[hypothesis]]ed that north-western Australia was the primary centre of origin for the two subspecies.<ref name="Ford">{{Cite journal|last=Ford|first=Julian|title=Origin, evolution and speciation of birds specialized to mangroves in Australia|journal=Emu|volume=82|pages=12–23|year=1982|issue=1 |doi=10.1071/MU9820012|bibcode=1982EmuAO..82...12F }}</ref>

== Description ==
[[File:Red-headed Honeyeaterf.jpg|thumb|right|Female perched on a [[paperbark]] branch]]

The red-headed myzomela is a distinctive small honeyeater with a compact body, short tail and relatively long down-curved bill. It averages {{convert|12|cm|in}}, with a wingspan of {{convert|17|-|19|cm|in|abbr=on}} and a weight of {{convert|8|g|oz}}. The birds exhibit [[sexual dimorphism]], with males being slightly larger and much more brightly coloured than females.{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1158}}

The adult male of the nominate subspecies has a dark red head, neck, and rump; the red is glossy, reflecting bright light. The rest of the upper body is a blackish-brown, and the upper breast and under-body a light brownish-grey. The red of the head is sharply demarcated against the brown plumage, giving the bird the appearance of having a red hood. The bill is black or blackish-brown, and the gape is black or yellowish. There is a distinct black [[Lore (anatomy)|loral]] stripe that extends to become a narrow eye ring. The iris is dark brown. The adult female's head and neck are grey-brown with a pink-red tint to the forehead and chin. The rest of the female's upper body is grey-brown with darker shades on the wings and lighter shades on the breast and underparts. The gape is yellow.{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1158}} One study suggested a connection between the female's bill colour and breeding status, with birds that had a horn-coloured (grey) bill also having well-developed [[brood patch]]es.<ref name="Lewis">{{Cite journal|last=Lewis|first=Jan|year=2010|title=Notes on the moult and biology of the Red-headed Honeyeater (''Myzomela erythrocephala'') in the west Kimberley, Western Australia|journal=Amytornis: Western Australian Journal of Ornithology|volume=2|pages=15–24|publisher=Birds Australia|location=Perth, Western Australia|issn=1836-3482 }}</ref> Juveniles are similar to females though with an obvious pale yellow edge to the lower [[mandible]].{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1158}} Initially lacking in red plumage, they begin to get red feathers on their faces after around a month of age.{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1164}} Males keep their juvenile plumage for up to three months, and take a similar period to come into full colour.<ref name="Lewis"/> ''M.&nbsp;e. infuscata'' is similar in appearance to the [[Subspecies|nominate race]] but has red extending from the rump onto the back, a darker grey belly, and is slightly larger overall.{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1164}}

The red-headed myzomela has a range of [[contact call]]s and songs that are primarily metallic or scratchy.{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1161}} Its song is an abrupt ''{{not a typo|tchwip-tchwip-tchwip-tchwip}}'' with a slightly softer ''{{not a typo|swip-swip-swip-swip}}'' contact call and a scolding ''{{not a typo|charrk-charrk}}''.<ref name="Guide"/>

The red-headed myzomela closely resembles the scarlet myzomela, though there is only a small overlap in their respective ranges, in eastern [[Cape York Peninsula]]. The latter species lives in woodlands rather than mangroves. The dusky myzomela resembles the female red-headed myzomela, but is larger and darker brown, and lacks the red markings around the bill.{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1159}} The Sumba myzomela is similar but slightly smaller than the red-headed myzomela and has darker upper parts and a broad black pectoral band.{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1164}}

== Distribution and habitat ==
[[File:Juvenile Male Red-Headed Honeyeater.jpg|thumb|right|A juvenile]]

The nominate subspecies of the red-headed myzomela is distributed across the tropical coastlines of Western Australia, the [[Northern Territory]] and [[Queensland]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Species profile—Myzomela erythrocephala (red-headed honeyeater) |url=https://apps.des.qld.gov.au/species-search/details/?id=1487 |access-date=2024-04-04 |website=Species information |publisher=Queensland Government}}</ref> It inhabits coastal areas of the [[Kimberley (Western Australia)|Kimberley]] and various offshore islands in Western Australia, and is similarly distributed in the Northern Territory, including [[Melville Island (Australia)|Melville Island]] and the [[Sir Edward Pellew Group of Islands]]. It is widespread around the coast of the [[Gulf of Carpentaria]] and the Cape York Peninsula.{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1159}} ''M.&nbsp;e. infuscata'' occurs at scattered sites in [[Papua (province)|West Papua]] and in south [[Papua New Guinea]], from the Mimika Regency in the west to the Fly River in the east, and the Aru Islands.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Beehler, Bruce M.|author2=Pratt, Thane K.|title=Birds of New Guinea: Distribution, Taxonomy, and Systematics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wRR1CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA292|year=2016|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-8071-3|pages=292–293}}</ref> Some birds of Cape York have features intermediate between the two subspecies.{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1164}}

Although the red-headed myzomela is widely distributed, it is not [[Abundance (ecology)|abundant]] within its range. The largest recorded population was 5.5 birds per [[hectare]] or 2.2 per acre at [[Palmerston, Northern Territory|Palmerston]] in the Northern Territory. The peak abundance of the species in the mangroves around [[Darwin Harbour]] during the mid-dry and early wet season coincided with the production of young and the flowering of the yellow mangrove (''[[Ceriops australis]]'').<ref name="Noske">{{Cite journal|last=Noske|first=Richard A.|title=Abundance, zonation and foraging ecology of birds in mangroves of Darwin Harbour, Northern Territory|journal=Wildlife Research|volume=23|issue=4|pages=443–474|issn=1035-3712|doi=10.1071/WR9960443|year=1996}}</ref>

The species' movements are poorly understood, variously described as [[Bird migration|resident, nomadic or migratory]].{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1160}} Population numbers have been reported as fluctuating in some areas with local movements possibly related to the flowering of preferred [[mangrove]] and ''[[Melaleuca]]'' food trees, and there is some indication that the birds can travel more widely.<ref name="Noske"/> A single bird was recaptured after being [[Bird ringing|band]]ed nearly five years earlier, {{convert|27|km|mi}} from the original banding site, and the species' occupation of a large number of offshore islands suggests that the red-headed myzomela is effective at crossing distances over water.<ref name="Lewis"/> The maximum age recorded from banding has been 7{{nbs}}years 1.5{{nbs}}months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.environment.gov.au/cgi-bin/biodiversity/abbbs/abbbs-search.pl|title=ABBBS Database Search: Myzomela erythrocephala (Red-headed Honeyeater)|author=Australian Bird & Bat Banding Scheme (ABBBS)|date=2017|work=Bird and bat banding database|publisher=Australian Government Department of the Environment, Water, Heritage and the Arts|access-date=25 February 2017}}</ref>

The red-headed myzomela mostly inhabits mangroves in [[monsoon]]al coastal areas, especially thickets of spotted mangrove (''[[Rhizophora stylosa]]''), smallflower bruguiera (''[[Bruguiera parviflora]]'') and grey mangrove (''[[Avicennia marina]]'') bordering islands or in [[river delta]]s, but it often also occurs in paperbark thickets fringing the mangroves such as those of cajeput (''[[Melaleuca leucadendra]]'').{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1159}} It is a mangrove specialist, an adaptation that probably occurred as northern Australia became more [[arid]] and the bird populations became dependent on mangroves as other types of forest disappeared.<ref name="Ford"/> The mangroves provide nectar and insects as well as shelter and nesting sites, and they supply the majority of the species' needs for most of the year.{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1161}} In Australia, mangrove vegetation forms a narrow discontinuous strip along thousands of kilometres of coastline, accommodating birds specialized for the [[habitat]].<ref name="Ford"/> [[Eighty Mile Beach]] in Western Australia has no mangroves and no fringing ''Melaleuca'' forests, reducing its potential for successful colonization by nectarivores, and it marks the southern limit of the red-headed myzomela in Western Australia.<ref name="Noske"/>

The red-headed myzomela is occasionally found in swampy woodlands, [[casuarina]] woodlands and open forest, particularly those with ''[[Pandanus]]'' and paperbarks, as well as on coconut farms.{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1159}}

== Behaviour ==
[[File:Myzomela erythrocephala.jpg|thumb|right|upright|A male on lookout]]

=== Social behaviour ===
While the social organisation of the red-headed myzomela is relatively unknown, it is reported as being usually solitary or found in pairs, though it has been described as forming loose associations with [[brown honeyeater]]s, and other mangrove-feeding birds such as the [[northern fantail]] and [[Canary white-eye|yellow white-eye]].<ref name="Noske"/> It is an inquisitive bird and readily responds to [[pish]]ing, coming close to the caller to investigate the source of the sound and to warn off the intruder. It calls throughout the day when feeding, and males sing from exposed branches in the upper [[Canopy (biology)|canopy]] of the food trees.{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1161}}

The red-headed myzomela actively defends food trees, engaging in aggressive bill-wiping both in response to a threat and after chasing intruders from a tree. It is very antagonistic even towards its own species; the males fight by grappling in mid-air and falling close to the ground before disengaging. It constantly chases brown honeyeaters through the canopy, though it has not been observed in grappling fights with other species.{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1161}}

=== Breeding ===
There are few scientific reports on the breeding behaviour of the red-headed myzomela, and little detail is available on the breeding season.{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1161}} A study of populations in the western Kimberley reported that the birds hold territories through much of the [[dry season]] and then disperse.<ref name="Noske"/> The nest is built in the foliage of the mangroves, suspended by a rim from a small horizontal fork about {{convert|6|-|10|m|ft|abbr=on}} above the ground or water. The nest is small and [[Cup nest|cup-shape]]d, and built from small pieces of bark, leaves, plant fibre and sometimes seaweed, bound together with [[spider web]] and lined with finer material. It is, on average, {{convert|5.4|cm|in|abbr=on}} in diameter and {{convert|3.7|cm|in|abbr=on}} deep.{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1161}}<!--cites previous three sentences-->

Measuring {{convert|16|by|12|mm|in|abbr=on}}, the eggs are oval, smooth and lustreless white, with small spots or blotches of red on the larger end. The clutch size is reported to be two or three eggs.<ref name="Nests">{{Cite book|last=Beruldsen|first=Gordon R.|author-link=Gordon Beruldsen|title=A Field Guide to Nests and Eggs of Australian Birds|publisher=self|location=Kenmore Hills, Queensland|orig-date=1980|year=2003|isbn=0-646-42798-9|page=329}}</ref> While there is no reliable information on incubation and feeding, it is believed that both parents are active in caring for the young.{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1162}} A field study by Jan Lewis and colleagues found that only females bore brood patches, suggesting they alone incubated eggs.<ref name="Lewis"/>

=== Feeding ===
The red-headed myzomela is arboreal, feeding at flowers and among the outer foliage in the crowns of mangroves and other flowering trees.<ref name="Guide">{{Cite book|last=Morcombe|first=Michael|title=Field Guide to Australian Birds|publisher=Steve Parrish Publishing|location=Archerfield, Queensland|year=2003|page=272|isbn=1-74021-417-X }}</ref> Very active when feeding, it darts from flower to flower, probing for nectar with its long curved bill. It [[Gleaning (birds)|gleans]] insects from foliage and twigs, as well as [[Hawking (birds)|sally]]ing for flying insects. Typical invertebrates eaten include spiders and insects such as [[coleoptera|beetles]], [[Hemiptera|bugs]], wasps, and caterpillars.{{sfn|Higgins|2001|p=1161}} The red-headed myzomela predominately feeds on mangrove species, and in north-western Australia is the major pollinator of the rib-fruited mangrove (''[[Bruguiera exaristata]]'');<ref name= "Biotropica">{{Cite journal|last=Noske|first=Richard A.|title=''Bruguiera hainesii'': another bird-pollinated mangrove?|journal=Biotropica|volume=25|issue=4|pages=481–483|year=1993|jstor=2388873|doi=10.2307/2388873|bibcode=1993Biotr..25..481N }}</ref> it also feeds in paperbarks and other coastal forests, and has been recorded feeding in cultivated [[Callistemon|bottlebrush]] and ''[[Grevillea]]'' in [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]] gardens, and silver-leaf grevillea (''[[Grevillea refracta]]'') and green birdflower (''[[Crotalaria cunninghamii]]''{{--)}} in northwest Western Australia. The red-headed myzomela may travel some distance from roosting areas to feed on plants in flower.<ref name="Lewis"/><!--cites previous two sentences-->

== Conservation status ==
''M. erythrocephala'' is listed as being of [[least concern]] by the [[IUCN]],<ref name="iucn status 25 September 2021"/> because the population is widespread. However, the Australian population of ''M.&nbsp;e. infuscata'' is listed as [[near threatened]], since it is confined to three small islands with a combined area of about {{convert|100|km2|sqmi}}.<ref name="Garnett">{{Citation|last1=Garnett|first1=Stephen|last2=Szabo|first2=Judith|last3=Dutson|first3=Guy|title=The Action Plan for Australian Birds 2010|place=Melbourne, Australia|publisher=CSIRO|year=2010|isbn=978-0-643-10368-9 }}</ref> There is no immediate threat to the red-headed myzomela, except the risk posed to low islands by rising sea levels;<ref name="Garnett"/> however, it has been recommended that community-based [[ecotourism]] on the tropical coast be promoted, as it could lead to monitoring of sub-populations and habitat by visiting birdwatchers and local rangers.<ref name="Garnett"/>

